'''Block, Inc.''' (formerly '''Square, Inc.''') is an American multinational technology [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] founded in 2009 by [[Jack Dorsey]] and [[Jim McKelvey]] and launched its first platform in 2010. It has been traded as a [[public company]] on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] since November 2015 with the ticker symbol SQ.

From its founding to December 10, 2021, the company was named Square, Inc.<ref>{{cite web|title=Form 8-K Report of Block, Inc.|url=https://www.sec.gov/ix?doc=/Archives/edgar/data/1512673/000119312521354007/d270905d8k.htm|publisher=U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|date=December 10, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jack Dorsey's Square changes corporate name to Block |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/12/01/square-changes-corporate-name-to-block-.html |website=CNBC |access-date=10 December 2021}}</ref> The company's namesake product for small businesses is still titled "[[Square (payment system)|Square]]".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Browning |first1=Kellen |title=Square, Jack Dorsey's payments company, changes its name to Block. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/01/technology/square-block-name-change-dorsey.html?action=click&module=Well&pgtype=Homepage&section=Technology |access-date=2 December 2021 |work=The New York Times |date=1 December 2021}}</ref>  Square is a payments platform aimed at small and medium businesses that allows them to accept credit card payments and use smartphone or tablet computers as payment registers for a [[Point-of-sale|point-of-sale system]]. Block has a number of other businesses. [[Cash App]] is a mobile app that allows monetary transfers both among users and between users and businesses. [[Afterpay]] is a [[Buy now, pay later|buy-now-pay-later]] service. [[Weebly]] is a [[web hosting service]]. [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] is a subscription-based music, podcast and video streaming service that offers audio and music videos.

==History==
The original inspiration for Square occurred to [[Jack Dorsey]] in 2009 when [[Jim McKelvey]] (a friend of Dorsey) was unable to complete a $2,000 sale of his glass faucets and fittings because he could not accept credit cards.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 11, 2010 |title=Square Brings Credit Card Swiping to the Mobile Masses, Starting Today |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1643271/square-brings-credit-card-swiping-mobile-masses-starting-today |access-date=September 19, 2011 |website=Fast Company}}</ref> Co-founders Dorsey—who also co-founded [[Twitter, Inc.|Twitter]]—and McKelvey began developing the company out of a small office in St. Louis.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2015-09-15 |title=Why Square's New Office Is A Really Big Deal for St. Louis |url=https://www.stlmag.com/news/why-square-new-office-is-a-really-big-deal-for-st-louis/ |work=St. Louis Magazine}}</ref> The name "Square" derives from the company's square-shaped card readers.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2011-05-26 |title=Square's name and design were changed by a lunch at Apple |url=https://thenextweb.com/apple/2011/05/26/squares-name-and-design-were-changed-by-a-lunch-at-apple/ |access-date=September 19, 2011 |publisher=thenextweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=May 26, 2011 |title=Square Was Almost Named Squirrel Until Dorsey Talked To Apple |url=http://pulse2.com/2011/05/26/square-was-almost-named-squirrel-until-dorsey-talked-to-apple/ |access-date=September 19, 2011 |publisher=pulse2.com}}</ref>

In October 2020, Square put approximately 1% of their total assets ($50 million) in [[Bitcoin]] (4,709 bitcoins), citing Bitcoin's "potential to be a more ubiquitous currency in the future" as their main reasoning.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Oliver Effron |title=Square just bought $50 million in bitcoin |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/10/08/business/square-bitcoin-crypto-investment/index.html |access-date=2020-10-22 |website=CNN|date=8 October 2020 }}</ref> The company purchased an additional $170 million worth of Bitcoin (approximately 3,318 bitcoins) in February 2021, bringing Square's total holdings to almost $500 million in Bitcoin (total approximately 8,027 bitcoins).<ref>{{Cite web|last=Bursztynsky|first=Jessica|date=2021-02-23|title=Square buys $170 million worth of bitcoin|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/02/23/square-buys-170-million-worth-of-bitcoin.html|access-date=2021-03-02|website=CNBC|language=en}}</ref>

On March 2, 2021, Square reached an agreement to acquire majority ownership in [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]. Square will pay $297 million in cash and stock for Tidal, with [[Jay-Z]] joining the company's board of directors. Jay-Z, as well as other artists who currently own stock in Tidal, will remain stakeholders.<ref>{{cite web |title=Square, Inc. to buy majority of Tidal and put Jay-Z on board |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/square-buy-majority-tidal-put-jay-board-76248384 |work=ABC News |agency=Associated Press |access-date=4 March 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy Kelly |first1=Samantha |title=Square to acquire majority stake in music service Tidal for $297 million |date=4 March 2021 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/03/04/tech/square-tidal/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=4 March 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Singleton |first1=Micah |title=Square Is Acquiring a Majority Stake in Tidal for $297M |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/streaming/9534646/square-tidal-acquisition-majority-stake-jay-z |magazine=Billboard |access-date=5 March 2021}}</ref>

On December 1, 2021, Square announced that it would change its company name to Block, Inc. on December 10.<ref name=wsj_block>{{Cite news|last=Vigna|first=Paul|date=2021-12-01|title=Square Changes Name to Block, Days After CEO Jack Dorsey Leaves Twitter|language=en-US|work=Wall Street Journal|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/square-changes-name-to-block-days-after-ceo-jack-dorsey-leaves-twitter-11638394200|access-date=2021-12-01|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release|date=2021-12-01|title=Square, Inc. Changes Name to Block|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20211201006139/en/Square-Inc.-Changes-Name-to-Block|access-date=2021-12-01|publisher=Block, Inc.|via=[[Business Wire]]|language=en}}</ref> The change was announced shortly after Dorsey resigned as CEO of Twitter.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Kurt |title=Square Changes Name to Block in Nod to New Businesses |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-12-01/dorsey-s-square-changes-name-to-block-in-nod-to-new-businesses?sref=CIpmV6x8 |access-date=2 December 2021 |work=Bloomberg |date=1 December 2021}}</ref> On December 10, 2021, the name change took effect, and Square, Inc. became Block.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jack Dorsey's Square changes corporate name to Block |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/12/01/square-changes-corporate-name-to-block-.html |website=CNBC |access-date=10 December 2021}}</ref> However, on December 16, less than a week into the rebrand, [[H&R Block]], sued the company for [[trademark infringement]], claiming that the name seeks to confuse customers by misappropriating the Block brand name, which H&R owns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-12-16/h-r-block-claims-jack-dorsey-s-block-inc-violates-trademark| title=H&R Block Is Suing Jack Dorsey's Block Over Name Change |website=Bloomberg |access-date=December 16, 2021}}</ref>

On January 31, 2022, Block completed its acquisition of [[Afterpay]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Block, Inc. Completes Acquisition of Afterpay|url=https://investors.block.xyz/news/news-details/2022/Block-Inc.-Completes-Acquisition-of-Afterpay/default.aspx|publisher=Block, Inc.|date=January 31, 2022}}</ref>

==Subsidiaries, products, services==

===Square===
{{Main|Square (payment system)}}
Square is a payments platform aimed at small and medium businesses that allows them to accept credit card payments and use tablet computers as payment registers for a [[Point-of-sale|point-of-sale system]]. The platform was founded in 2009 by Twitter Co-Founder Jack Dorsey and fellow entrepreneur Jim McKelvey.<ref>{{Cite web |title=What Is Square, Inc.? |url=https://www.investopedia.com/articles/tech/021017/square.asp |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=Investopedia |language=en}}</ref> Their goal was to create a POS technology that would group together merchant services and mobile payments into one, simple, smooth, and modern service. Currently, businesses in 8 countries can use Square’s Technology, and their POS systems can accept 130 internationally accepted currencies.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Square Point of Sale: Now Available Worldwide |url=https://squareup.com/us/en/townsquare/square-register-app-now-available-worldwide |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=Square |language=en-US}}</ref>

===Cash App===
{{Main|Cash App}}

Launched in October 2013, [[Cash App]] (formerly Square Cash) allows person-to-person money transfer via the app or website.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hamburger |first=Ellis |date=2013-10-15 |title=Square Cash lets anyone with a debit card send money instantly over email |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/10/15/4842518/square-cash-send-money-over-email-iphone-android |access-date=2020-12-20 |website=The Verge |language=en}}</ref> Cash App reported 36 million monthly active Cash App customers as of December 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Bary|first=Emily|title=Square's 'Year of the Cash App' finishes with debate over profits|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/squares-year-of-the-cash-app-finishes-with-debate-over-profits-11614181689|access-date=2021-02-28|website=MarketWatch|language=en-US}}</ref>

In March 2015, the firm introduced Square Cash for businesses, which includes the ability for individuals, organizations, and business owners to use a unique username, known as a $cashtag, to send and receive money.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 23, 2015 |title=Square Introduces Square Cash for Businesses, With a Low 1.5 Percent Processing Fee |url=http://recode.net/2015/03/23/square-introduces-square-cash-for-businesses-with-a-low-1-5-percent-processing-fee/ |work=Re/code}}</ref> In January 2018, the app expanded to allow users to buy and sell [[bitcoin]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tepper |first=Fitz |title=Square Cash expands bitcoin buying and selling to all users |language=en |work=TechCrunch |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/01/31/square-cash-expands-bitcoin-buying-and-selling-to-all-users/ |access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> Additionally they began offering stock trading. The company issues a [[debit card]] to be used with the account.<ref>{{Cite web |date=February 20, 2019 |title=Square Cash Card Review (2019) |url=https://dyernews.com/square-cash-card-review/ |access-date=December 22, 2019 |website=Dyer News}}</ref> Cash App is currently testing new features to allow users to borrow up to $200.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Square's Cash App tests money borrowing for up to $200 |url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2020/08/12/square-cash-app-borrowing/ |access-date=2020-08-14 |website=TechCrunch |date=12 August 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref>

===Afterpay===
{{Main|Afterpay}}
Afterpay is an Australian digital payment platform in which a bought product can be paid off in four installments. This idea made in 2008 by a then eighteen-year-old Nick Molnar was geared towards millennials and inspired by the aftermath of the 2008 Global Financial Crisis. Molnar and Partner/ Co-founder Anthony Eisen launched their platform in 2014 and in four years their product reached a market capitalization of around $3.3 billion dollars. In February 2020, Afterpay was reported to have 3.6 million active customers in the US, 3.1 million in Australia and New Zealand, and 600,000 in the UK. In August 2021, Afterpay and Square announced that Afterpay would be acquired by Square.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-08-01 |title=Afterpay to be acquired by Square in $39 billion deal |url=https://www.smartcompany.com.au/startupsmart/news/afterpay-acquired-square-39-billion/ |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=SmartCompany |language=en-US}}</ref> Block paid US$29 billion in stock for the acquisition and the process was finalized in January 2022.<ref name="completed acquistion">{{cite press release|title=Block, Inc. Completes Acquisition of Afterpay|url=https://investors.block.xyz/news/news-details/2022/Block-Inc.-Completes-Acquisition-of-Afterpay/default.aspx|publisher=Block, Inc.|date=January 31, 2022}}</ref> Although Afterpay is now owned by Block inc., Molnar and Eisen still spearhead Afterpay’s merchant and consumer businesses.

===Weebly===
{{Main|Weebly}}
[[Weebly]] is a [[web hosting service]]. Weebly was founded in 2006 by David Rusenko, Dan Veltri, and Chris Fanini after they all met as students at Pennsylvania State University.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Levy |first=Steven |date=2007-05-20 |title=A Boot Camp for the Next Tech Billionaires |url=https://www.newsweek.com/boot-camp-next-tech-billionaires-100977 |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=Newsweek |language=en}}</ref> In 2007, Weebly raised $650,000 in initial capital from a group of angel investors. In 2018, Square Inc. (Now Block Inc.) bought Weebly in exchange for $365 million in cash and stock.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Square is acquiring website builder Weebly for $365M |url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2018/04/26/square-acquires-weebly/ |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=TechCrunch |date=26 April 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> The company slowly grew and updated its capabilities over the course of a decade and now Weebly is a free online website creator that operates out of the web browser. The site offers users access to drag and drop features to build their websites, with unlimited storage options and custom URLs.

===Tidal===
{{Main|Tidal (service)}}
Tidal is a digital music streaming service that gives users access to over 80 million songs from genres and artists across the world.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pocket-lint |date=2022-02-03 |title=What is Tidal and how does it work? |url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/apps/news/133451-what-is-tidal-and-why-should-you-care |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=www.pocket-lint.com |language=en-gb}}</ref> Tidal was founded on the basis of artists getting paid rightfully for their work, meaning fully and directly instead of through traditional means. Tidal was first launched in 2014 by a Norwegian company called Aspiro. Aspiro was purchased by Jay-Z in 2015 for $56 million.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sisario |first=Ben |date=2015-03-13 |title=Jay Z Buys the Music Streaming Firm, Aspiro |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/14/business/media/jay-z-buys-the-music-streaming-firm-aspiro.html |access-date=2022-04-25 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In early 2017, the Sprint Corporation purchased 33% of the company for $200 million and then in 2021 Square Inc. paid $297 million for a majority ownership of the company.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Square, Inc. Announces Plans To Acquire Majority Ownership Stake In TIDAL |url=https://squareup.com/us/en/press/tidal |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=Square |language=en-US}}</ref> Tidal now operates in 61 countries worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pocket-lint |date=2022-02-03 |title=What is Tidal and how does it work? |url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/apps/news/133451-what-is-tidal-and-why-should-you-care |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=www.pocket-lint.com |language=en-gb}}</ref> In June, 2022, through the disclosure of the Annual Stockholder Meeting 2022, Block reported that the stake acquired in the Tidal music service was 86.8%.<ref name=AnnualStockholderMeeting2022>{{Cite web|url=https://s29.q4cdn.com/628966176/files/doc_presentations/2022/06/Block-Annual-Report-2022.pdf|title = Page 188 from Block, Inc. Annual Stockholder Meeting 2022}}</ref>

==Financials==
Square received [[Angel investor|angel investments]] from [[Marissa Mayer]], [[Kevin Rose]], [[Biz Stone]], [[Dennis Crowley]], [[Shawn Fanning]], [[MC Hammer]], and [[Esther Dyson]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} Since then, it has raised several additional rounds of funding:
* Series A funding from [[Khosla Ventures]]<ref name=rounds />
* Series B funding from [[Sequoia Capital]]<ref name=rounds />
* Series C funding from [[Kleiner Perkins]]<ref name=rounds>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/11/09/square-ipo-will-net-big-win-for-one-firm.html |title=On paper, Khosla's firm could net a massive return on Square IPO |date=9 November 2015 |work=[[CNBC]] |last=Taylor |first=Harriet}}</ref>
* Series D funding from [[Citigroup|Citi Ventures]], Rizvi Traverse Management, and [[Starbucks]]<ref name="seriesD">{{Cite web |last=Square Inc. |date=December 18, 2014 |title=Square A milestone: We're now 1,000 employees strong. |url=https://www.linkedin.com/company/square |access-date=December 18, 2014 |publisher=Linkedin.com}}</ref>
* Series E funding from [[Goldman Sachs]], Rizvi Traverse Management, and [[GIC Private Limited]]<ref>{{Cite news |last=Isaac |first=Mike |date=October 5, 2014 |title=Square Raises $150 Million at a $6 Billion Valuation |work=The New York Times |url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/05/square-raises-150-million-at-a-6-billion-valuation/?_r=0}}</ref>

The company's valuation in October 2014 was $6 billion.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rao |first=Leena |date=October 5, 2014 |title=Square Closes $150 Million Round At $6 Billion Valuation |work=Fortune |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/10/05/square-closes-150-round-at-6-billion-valuation/}}</ref> On November 19, 2015, Square had its IPO on the New York Stock Exchange with an initial valuation of $2.9 billion, down by more than half from its last valuation in October 2014 at $6 billion. The series E funding shares had different rights than the common shares sold at the IPO, therefore the $6 billion 'valuation' from October 2014 is wrong.  Although the firm was yet to make a profit as of 2015 and had lost $420 million since 2012, it had decreased its losses from 44% of revenues to 16% in the six months leading up to its IPO.<ref name="economist_ipo">{{Cite news |date=21 November 2015 |title=Square's IPO: Swiped |publisher=The Economist |url=https://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21678809-profitless-payment-firm-goes-public-swiped |access-date=20 November 2015}}</ref> For the fiscal year 2018, Square reported losses of US$38 million, with an annual revenue of US$3.299 billion, an increase of 49.0% over the previous fiscal cycle.

